4
00:02:01,417 --> 00:02:04,087
<i>A day where lives are changed,

5
00:02:04,667 --> 00:02:07,212
<i>fates are decided,

6
00:02:07,458 --> 00:02:10,207
<i>dynasties are born,

7
00:02:10,208 --> 00:02:13,834
<i>and the clock is always ticking.

8
00:02:14,125 --> 00:02:16,216
<i>Of course,

9
00:02:16,458 --> 00:02:18,291
<i>I'm talking about...

10
00:02:48,584 --> 00:02:50,083
Hello.

11
00:02:51,792 --> 00:02:53,291
Yes, sir.

12
00:02:54,625 --> 00:02:56,124
Sir?

13
00:02:57,125 --> 00:02:58,207
What is it?

14
00:02:58,208 --> 00:03:00,379
He's waiting in his office.

15
00:03:00,500 --> 00:03:01,791
What time is it?

16
00:03:01,792 --> 00:03:03,291
4:15.

17
00:03:08,292 --> 00:03:09,666
What are we gonna do with it?

18
00:03:09,667 --> 00:03:12,875
Well, we've gone over
this a lot, Walt.

19
00:03:12,876 --> 00:03:15,207
I'm really nervous about
trading away the top pick.

20
00:03:15,208 --> 00:03:16,332
Callahan could be huge.

21
00:03:16,333 --> 00:03:17,583
That's true.

22
00:03:17,584 --> 00:03:19,583
But it might be worth it if
someone's willing to give us

23
00:03:19,584 --> 00:03:22,124
their weight in gold to get him.

24
00:03:22,125 --> 00:03:23,249
What'd the Rams get

25
00:03:23,250 --> 00:03:24,958
when they traded away
number two overall

26
00:03:24,959 --> 00:03:26,624
to the Redskins a few years back?

27
00:03:26,625 --> 00:03:29,457
Three number one picks
and a number two.

28
00:03:29,458 --> 00:03:31,291
Well, shit, that'd work for me.

29
00:03:31,292 --> 00:03:33,541
Nobody's offering us that, Walt.

30
00:03:33,542 --> 00:03:35,087
Look.

31
00:03:35,709 --> 00:03:38,583
Do you want the entire city of
Seattle calling for our heads

32
00:03:38,584 --> 00:03:41,675
because we didn't pick Bo Callahan?

33
00:03:43,000 --> 00:03:46,082
Our fans know a good deal
when they see one, Tom.

34
00:03:46,083 --> 00:03:48,666
Which is why we're not even
gonna think about doing this

35
00:03:48,667 --> 00:03:50,207
unless we can find someone...

36
00:03:50,208 --> 00:03:52,166
Stupid enough to give
us more than he should.

37
00:03:52,167 --> 00:03:53,249
Exactly.

38
00:03:53,250 --> 00:03:54,875
So,

39
00:03:56,125 --> 00:03:59,296
who's the most desperate
guy you know?

40
00:04:08,375 --> 00:04:09,999
<i>We got a fun one today,
don't we, fellas?

41
00:04:10,000 --> 00:04:11,249
<i>Boom, more intrigue this year

42
00:04:11,250 --> 00:04:12,583
<i>than I can remember in a long time.

43
00:04:12,584 --> 00:04:14,583
<i>There's no intrigue at
the number one pick.

44
00:04:15,876 --> 00:04:18,374
<i>Bo Callahan, Wisconsin Badger,
overall number one to Seattle.

45
00:04:18,375 --> 00:04:19,457
<i>That's gotta be a slam dunk.

46
00:04:19,458 --> 00:04:20,749
<i>We haven't had a
quarterback like this

47
00:04:20,750 --> 00:04:22,499
<i>enter the Draft since Andrew Luck.

48
00:04:22,500 --> 00:04:23,875
<i>Right, so you got the
Heisman Trophy winner

49
00:04:23,876 --> 00:04:25,457
<i>going to the Seahawks.

50
00:04:25,458 --> 00:04:28,207
<i>But what about the other 31 teams?
What are they gonna do?

51
00:04:28,208 --> 00:04:29,791
<i>Who you lookin' at today, Jon? Mel?

52
00:04:29,792 --> 00:04:31,915
<i>I think it's Cleveland
at number seven.

53
00:04:31,916 --> 00:04:34,124
<i>Sonny Weaver Jr., he's gotta have
a lot on his mind this year.

54
00:04:34,125 --> 00:04:35,207
<i>I'm with Mel.

55
00:04:35,208 --> 00:04:38,915
<i>As we all know, Sonny's dad, former
Browns coach Sonny Weaver Sr.,

56
00:04:38,916 --> 00:04:41,499
<i>he's a legend in Cleveland,
he died last week.

57
00:04:41,500 --> 00:04:45,207
<i>This kid, Ray Jennings, Heisman
Trophy finalist his senior year.

58
00:04:45,208 --> 00:04:48,749
<i>2,159 combined yards,
running the ball,

59
00:04:48,750 --> 00:04:50,833
<i>catching the ball, 22 touchdowns.

60
00:04:50,834 --> 00:04:52,499
<i>He's looking to take
it to the house.

61
00:04:52,500 --> 00:04:55,416
<i>The only downfall is this guy
got into a little skirmish.

62
00:04:55,417 --> 00:04:58,416
<i>Assault and battery, landed
a kid in the hospital.

63
00:04:58,417 --> 00:05:01,875
<i>But guess what? He was a
model citizen up until then.

64
00:05:01,876 --> 00:05:04,082
<i>And you guys know me.
I'm all about values.

65
00:05:04,083 --> 00:05:06,082
<i>And this kid's number
two on my board.

66
00:05:06,083 --> 00:05:08,332
<i>And when I look at that
incident, I kind of say, "Look.

67
00:05:08,333 --> 00:05:09,624
<i>"It's not medical,
it's not drug-related."

68
00:05:09,625 --> 00:05:11,291
Good morning.

69
00:05:11,292 --> 00:05:13,332
<i>So if I got a kid at number two,

70
00:05:13,333 --> 00:05:15,749
<i>and he's slidin' down
towards number seven...

71
00:05:25,333 --> 00:05:27,208
You look nice.

72
00:05:28,750 --> 00:05:31,040
Are you gonna say anything to me?

73
00:05:31,041 --> 00:05:33,291
Anything at all?

74
00:05:34,584 --> 00:05:36,040
Well, it's big.

75
00:05:36,041 --> 00:05:38,382
It's a pretty big thing
we're talkin' about here.

76
00:05:43,292 --> 00:05:44,957
Look.

77
00:05:44,958 --> 00:05:48,583
You can understand why
this week, of all weeks,

78
00:05:48,584 --> 00:05:50,583
I might feel just a
little conflicted about

79
00:05:50,584 --> 00:05:52,708
the news I'm suddenly
gonna be a dad.

80
00:05:52,709 --> 00:05:54,124
I know.

81
00:05:54,125 --> 00:05:56,091
Shit timing.

82
00:06:12,250 --> 00:06:13,332
Hey!

83
00:06:14,417 --> 00:06:16,212
Hey!

84
00:06:21,041 --> 00:06:23,166
Where are you goin'?

85
00:06:23,250 --> 00:06:25,124
I need to go to my
place before work.

86
00:06:26,500 --> 00:06:28,082
Look, I'm, uh...

87
00:06:36,292 --> 00:06:37,791
Shit.

88
00:06:42,584 --> 00:06:44,790
Hey, Tom. You're up early.

89
00:06:44,791 --> 00:06:46,583
<i>Well, it is Draft Day.

90
00:06:46,584 --> 00:06:48,166
<i>How're you doin'?

91
00:06:48,167 --> 00:06:49,666
Uh... Well, I'm great.
I'm havin' a great day.

92
00:06:49,667 --> 00:06:50,915
How 'bout you?

93
00:06:50,916 --> 00:06:53,667
Well, I'm sittin' here,
eatin' my pancakes,

94
00:06:54,542 --> 00:06:56,499
thinkin' about movin' number one.

95
00:06:56,500 --> 00:06:57,790
Really?

96
00:06:57,791 --> 00:07:02,837
<i>Yeah, as you know, Connors did
a great job for us last year.

97
00:07:02,958 --> 00:07:04,790
But Callahan looks like...

98
00:07:04,791 --> 00:07:05,999
Well, hell, Sonny, he's gonna be

99
00:07:06,000 --> 00:07:08,332
a franchise player for someone.

100
00:07:08,333 --> 00:07:10,208
You'd consider a trade?

101
00:07:11,083 --> 00:07:13,549
I'd consider the right one.

102
00:07:17,584 --> 00:07:21,040
Well, Jesus, Tom, at least act
like you called me, all right?

103
00:07:21,041 --> 00:07:22,499
What do you want for it?

104
00:07:22,500 --> 00:07:25,999
I want your first pick this year,
your first-rounder next year,

105
00:07:26,000 --> 00:07:27,666
and your third-rounder
the year after that.

106
00:07:27,667 --> 00:07:30,207
Ouch. Ouch. No, thanks.

107
00:07:30,208 --> 00:07:31,291
I know what it sounds like...

108
00:07:31,292 --> 00:07:33,124
It sounds like you're trying
to take advantage of me.

109
00:07:33,125 --> 00:07:34,583
I would never do that.

110
00:07:34,584 --> 00:07:36,332
Your seventh pick gives you, what?

111
00:07:36,333 --> 00:07:37,957
A running back with a rap sheet?

112
00:07:37,958 --> 00:07:39,457
You don't know who I'm
pickin' seven, Tom.

113
00:07:39,458 --> 00:07:41,624
I'm not gonna sell the
farm for one guy.

114
00:07:41,625 --> 00:07:43,124
Well...

115
00:07:43,584 --> 00:07:46,425
You should. Your farm sucks.

116
00:07:46,625 --> 00:07:48,291
Pick number one.

117
00:07:48,292 --> 00:07:49,457
Get Bo Callahan.

118
00:07:49,458 --> 00:07:50,541
I got a quarterback.

119
00:07:50,542 --> 00:07:52,041
Brian Drew?

120
00:07:52,584 --> 00:07:54,629
Are you talking about Brian Drew?

121
00:07:54,667 --> 00:07:56,374
Jesus, you're hilarious.

122
00:07:56,375 --> 00:07:57,999
Guy barely made it
through half the season

123
00:07:58,000 --> 00:07:59,915
before gettin' injured last year.

124
00:07:59,916 --> 00:08:02,082
I have the golden ticket, Sonny.

125
00:08:02,083 --> 00:08:06,459
If I give it to you, you get
to save football in Cleveland.

126
00:08:10,000 --> 00:08:13,546
You have 10 seconds, but
then I gotta go to work.

127
00:08:16,958 --> 00:08:19,504
Enjoy your pancakes, Tom.

128
00:08:26,667 --> 00:08:28,666
<i>Folks, I believe the
word "Clevelander"

129
00:08:28,667 --> 00:08:32,874
<i>comes from the Latin word that means
"to have idiotic hope at all time,"

130
00:08:32,875 --> 00:08:35,249
<i>and don't we ever?

131
00:08:35,250 --> 00:08:39,583
<i>We don't have beaches and
beautiful weather and sunshine

132
00:08:39,584 --> 00:08:42,166
<i>and hot babes
roller-skating all over.

133
00:08:42,167 --> 00:08:43,874
<i>You know what we've got?

134
00:08:43,875 --> 00:08:46,541
<i>We got our sports teams.

135
00:08:46,542 --> 00:08:48,166
<i>And that's the only hope we have.

136
00:08:48,167 --> 00:08:49,874
<i>Let me explain to you.

137
00:08:49,875 --> 00:08:53,790
<i>Football was invented 20 miles
down the road in Canton, Ohio.

138
00:08:53,791 --> 00:08:56,748
<i>This is a football town.
It's in our DNA.

139
00:08:56,749 --> 00:08:58,124
<i>No doubt about it.

140
00:08:58,125 --> 00:09:00,790
<i>To me, losing the team altogether,

141
00:09:00,791 --> 00:09:05,832
<i>having the team go and move to
Baltimore, go there and win,

142
00:09:05,833 --> 00:09:07,915
<i>that was so painful for the town.

143
00:09:07,916 --> 00:09:11,962
<i>And then the new expansion
franchise having to come back in.

144
00:09:12,375 --> 00:09:14,416
<i>One of the amazing
things to me is that,

145
00:09:14,417 --> 00:09:18,416
<i>in the midst of all of this losing,
people are still hopeful that...

146
00:09:18,417 --> 00:09:22,499
<i>- Yeah.
- ...eventually, this is going to be our year.

147
00:09:22,500 --> 00:09:26,249
<i>Maybe to a fault, with the hope.
But that's really all we have.

148
00:09:26,250 --> 00:09:29,457
<i>- Because this is a sports town.
- And I want Sonny Weaver to know...

149
00:09:29,458 --> 00:09:31,249
<i>Sonny, I hope you're listening.
You better be.

150
00:09:31,250 --> 00:09:35,707
<i>Can you please do somethin' tonight
to turn this thing around?

151
00:09:35,708 --> 00:09:39,425
<i>- Otherwise, you will be gone.

152
00:09:39,916 --> 00:09:40,999
Hello?

153
00:09:41,000 --> 00:09:43,707
Good morning, Mr. Sonny Weaver Jr.

154
00:09:43,708 --> 00:09:46,707
It's your number one
fan, Vontae Mack.

155
00:09:46,708 --> 00:09:48,541
Vontae, how'd you get this number?

156
00:09:48,542 --> 00:09:51,462
You gave it to me. At the Combine.

157
00:09:51,584 --> 00:09:53,207
It's all right if I called?

158
00:09:53,208 --> 00:09:54,707
That's all right.
It doesn't matter.

159
00:09:54,708 --> 00:09:57,541
Vontae, the Draft doesn't
start until 8:00.

160
00:09:57,542 --> 00:09:59,124
Where are you? New York?

161
00:09:59,125 --> 00:10:00,623
Naw, man.

162
00:10:00,624 --> 00:10:02,999
They wanted me up
there at Radio City,

163
00:10:03,000 --> 00:10:05,670
but I wanted to be here in
Virginia with my grams.

164
00:10:05,916 --> 00:10:08,791
Since she old, she
can't make that trip.

165
00:10:09,208 --> 00:10:10,707
So?

166
00:10:11,000 --> 00:10:12,915
Who you picking?

167
00:10:12,916 --> 00:10:14,040
If I was you,

168
00:10:14,041 --> 00:10:16,207
I'd take a lightning-quick
middle linebacker

169
00:10:16,208 --> 00:10:18,753
who can murder the gaps in a 3-4.

170
00:10:18,875 --> 00:10:20,124
Totally agree.

171
00:10:20,125 --> 00:10:22,707
You got Reggie Wilson's
number down there in Purdue?

172
00:10:22,708 --> 00:10:25,124
Now, I really don't
find that funny.

173
00:10:25,125 --> 00:10:28,499
Yeah, it's funny, Vontae. You're
just not feelin' it right now.

174
00:10:28,500 --> 00:10:31,665
Look, there's gonna be a lot of ups
and downs before this is all over.

175
00:10:31,666 --> 00:10:33,748
Try and keep a sense of humor.

176
00:10:33,749 --> 00:10:35,707
I ain't stupid.

177
00:10:35,708 --> 00:10:39,665
You don't take me at seven,
I'll drop down to the late teens.

178
00:10:39,666 --> 00:10:41,040
I watch the mock drafts!

179
00:10:41,041 --> 00:10:44,249
I know who takin' who and I
can't afford to fall that far.

180
00:10:44,250 --> 00:10:46,665
I can't take no
late-teens paycheck.

181
00:10:46,666 --> 00:10:49,582
Vontae needs a seven-pick paycheck.

182
00:10:49,583 --> 00:10:52,416
I got a gaggle of nephews
who need to get fed now.

183
00:10:52,417 --> 00:10:53,748
I'm taking 'em tumblin'.

184
00:10:53,749 --> 00:10:56,207
- Nephews, you love tumbling, yes or no?
- Yes!

185
00:10:56,208 --> 00:10:58,332
See, that's the difference
between them and me.

186
00:10:58,333 --> 00:11:03,832
I do not like tumblin'. Especially
if I'm tumbling 13 picks. Feel me?

187
00:11:03,833 --> 00:11:05,207
<i>Seventh pick...

188
00:11:05,208 --> 00:11:07,253
Listen, I appreciate that,
Vontae, I really do.

189
00:11:07,375 --> 00:11:09,166
- But I gotta go.
<i>- Seventeen or 18...

190
00:11:09,167 --> 00:11:10,882
<i>Then I got tax...

191
00:11:22,125 --> 00:11:23,291
Y'all ready to go?

192
00:11:23,292 --> 00:11:24,374
Yes!

193
00:11:24,375 --> 00:11:26,166
- Y'all ready to tumble?
- Yes!

194
00:11:26,167 --> 00:11:27,416
- Yes?
- Yes!

195
00:11:27,417 --> 00:11:29,292
That's what I want!

196
00:11:35,292 --> 00:11:36,374
<i>Hello?

197
00:11:36,375 --> 00:11:38,207
Sonny. Earl Jennings.

198
00:11:38,208 --> 00:11:41,083
- Hey, Earl. You're with your boy today?
- <i>Yeah.

199
00:11:41,417 --> 00:11:43,374
You guys in the Big Apple?

200
00:11:43,375 --> 00:11:45,623
<i>Listen, Sonny.

201
00:11:45,624 --> 00:11:48,332
It's none of my business who
you draft today, all right?

202
00:11:48,333 --> 00:11:51,458
Ray will play for
whoever wants him.

203
00:11:51,541 --> 00:11:53,874
But if you're thinkin'
of pickin' him...

204
00:11:53,875 --> 00:11:56,249
I need you to know that
I raised Ray right.

205
00:11:56,250 --> 00:11:58,707
C'mon, Earl. I know
what the papers say.

206
00:11:58,708 --> 00:12:01,174
<i>I'll have him explain it to you.

207
00:12:01,208 --> 00:12:02,874
<i>What's goin' on, Mr. Weaver?

208
00:12:02,875 --> 00:12:03,915
<i>First of all,

209
00:12:03,916 --> 00:12:06,124
I'm not in a gang.

210
00:12:06,125 --> 00:12:08,416
The guys that were with
me, I grew up with them,

211
00:12:08,417 --> 00:12:10,707
I've known 'em since I was a kid.

212
00:12:10,708 --> 00:12:13,832
But the dudes we ran into,

213
00:12:13,833 --> 00:12:17,249
they were big dudes,
and they came at us.

214
00:12:17,250 --> 00:12:19,207
What was I supposed to
do, just stand there?

215
00:12:19,208 --> 00:12:21,498
Well, they say you whooped
on that kid pretty good, Ray.

216
00:12:21,499 --> 00:12:22,874
He's still in the hospital.

217
00:12:22,875 --> 00:12:24,332
<i>He's not a kid.

218
00:12:24,333 --> 00:12:26,915
None of 'em were.
They were grown men.

219
00:12:26,916 --> 00:12:28,416
They should have known
better, Mr. Weaver.

220
00:12:28,417 --> 00:12:30,999
Well, that's not the point.

221
00:12:31,000 --> 00:12:32,795
Did you hurt your hands?

222
00:12:34,499 --> 00:12:35,790
<i>You need your hands, Ray.

223
00:12:35,791 --> 00:12:37,461
I know.

224
00:12:39,250 --> 00:12:41,091
I just lost my head.

225
00:12:41,541 --> 00:12:43,041
<i>Did you find it?

226
00:12:43,749 --> 00:12:45,082
Yes, sir.

227
00:12:45,083 --> 00:12:47,915
Well, good. Now hold on
to it, you understand me?

228
00:12:47,916 --> 00:12:49,416
<i>Yes, sir.

229
00:12:50,250 --> 00:12:52,124
Enjoy today, Ray.

230
00:12:52,125 --> 00:12:54,332
You only get drafted once.

231
00:12:54,333 --> 00:12:56,832
Yes, sir. I appreciate
that, Mr. Weaver.

232
00:13:04,749 --> 00:13:06,590
Ah...

233
00:13:06,666 --> 00:13:08,541
Jesus...

234
00:13:09,125 --> 00:13:11,707
What? What'd he say?

235
00:13:13,624 --> 00:13:17,374
I just wanna be a Brown.
Like you, Pop.

236
00:13:17,375 --> 00:13:20,125
Yeah, I want that, too.

237
00:13:20,167 --> 00:13:23,957
But you'll play where you play.
That's the way it works.

238
00:13:23,958 --> 00:13:25,665
I know.

239
00:13:25,666 --> 00:13:27,962
I'm just nervous, man.

240
00:13:28,833 --> 00:13:31,957
You see that? That's
the Dungeon Drop.

241
00:13:31,958 --> 00:13:34,540
Kids waited an hour to take it.

242
00:13:34,541 --> 00:13:38,456
It's exactly 50 feet from the end
of the slide right into the pool.

243
00:13:38,457 --> 00:13:39,999
Huge splash.

244
00:13:40,000 --> 00:13:41,623
Anybody within shouting distance

245
00:13:41,624 --> 00:13:43,456
would've gotten completely soaked.

246
00:13:43,457 --> 00:13:45,623
And people pay for that.

247
00:13:45,624 --> 00:13:49,040
I need you to make a splash,
